      \field{abstract}{{$<$}p{$>$}1. Agricultural intensification can support the expansion of introduced species which are highly adapted to human-modified landscapes, but the mechanisms by which this occurs are often unclear. 2. Here we investigate the spatial ecology of a rapidly expanding introduced bumble bee (\mkbibemph{Bombus impatiens}) and a native congener (\mkbibemph{B. mixtus}) in agricultural landscapes of southwestern British Columbia, Canada. We used microsatellite genotyping and spatially explicit capture-recapture models to compare the foraging distance of the two species, and fitted hierarchical models to compare their abundance, behaviour (nest searching vs foraging), and lineage survival as a function of landscape composition and configuration. 3. We found that \mkbibemph{B. impatiens} had a broader foraging range than \mkbibemph{B. mixtus}, and that its colony/worker abundance were positively associated with the surrounding area of residential gardens, but decreased relative to \mkbibemph{B. mixtus} abundance in response to increasing seminatural area. In contrast, \mkbibemph{B. mixtus} colony abundance decreased in landscapes with a greater area of intensively managed berry crops. 4. We observed fewer \mkbibemph{B. impatiens} queens per survey in landscapes with more low-disturbance landcover, and hypothesize space use of this species could be shaped by concentration on potential nesting habitat. Consistent with this observation, nest searching behaviour was more common for \mkbibemph{B. impatiens} queens, while \mkbibemph{B. mixtus} queens were primarily observed foraging, suggesting these two species derive different value from agricultural landscapes during colony establishment. 5. Finally, we found that the rate of lineage re-capture between 2022 colonies and 2023 spring queens was nearly 10-fold higher for \mkbibemph{B. impatiens} than for \mkbibemph{B. mixtus}, indicating a greater capacity of the introduced species to complete its life cycle in agro-natural landscape mosaics. 6. Our results suggest that differences in spatial ecology may contribute to the differential success of these two species in human-modified landscapes, and provide insight into the mechanisms by which land-use change shapes community composition.{$<$}/p{$>$}}
